@node "What" "EPSRename -- What is this?"
@next "Install"
@prev "Main"

    @{fg shine}What is EPSRename?@{fg text}
   --------------------


Have you ever obtained a CDROM full of EPSF clipart images with their
filenames the maximum lenght of 8 characters?

This program is a helping tool for transfering PostScript Clip Art
images. The basic function of this program is to copy PS files from
devices like CDROMs, Streamers etc. (or any other storage devices) to
any devices you wish (e.g. your hard drive). There are many useful
features you've got in this program.

The most important feature is obtaining a real title of each image, and
renaming images' filenames to their true full lenght names. Do you ever
get confused when trying to figure out what kind of image does a ClipArt
file named 'CHRSMSTR.PS' or 'ARCHHOUS.EPS' represent?


Did you know that each PS file contains a lot of information about
itself:
 - the original real name (not 'CHRSMSTR.PS' but 'Christmass Tree.ps')
 - which program was an image created with
 - a creation date


With EPSRename you are able to copy PS files, to rename files with their
real names, to retrieve images' creation dates, and to put creator names
in file notes.

EPS Rename will also check each file you select, whether it is a clipart
PS file or not, and will skip all no-PS files.
@endnode

@node "Install" "EPS Rename -- How to install it?"
@next "Usage"
@prev "What"

    @{fg shine}How to install EPSRename?@{fg text}
   ---------------------------


This couldn't be easier. There is only one executable program. Just copy
EPSRename to any place you want (drag EPSRename's icon to a drawer you
want to be copied into).
@endnode

@node "Usage" "EPSRename -- How to use it?"
@next "Author"
@prev "Install"
    @{fg shine}How to use EPSRename?@{fg text}
   -----------------------


First you should choose source EPS files that you want to copy. For a
file/dir requester you can click on a gadget at the very right edge of
the window, or you can type a source path into a string field to get a
file requester where you can select multiple files and dirs. If you
select a directory, all files in this dir and in all subdirs within this
directory will be copied (this directory and all subdirs will
automaticaly be created on a destination path).

After that you may select or type in a destination path where you want
to copy selected files to.


You have five options, explaining how to copy selected EPS files:

 - EXTENSION UPPER CASE: All copied files will have their extension in
   upper case (extension is a part of a filename after the last '.')

 - MAKE FILENAME CAPITALIZED: Filenames excluding extension names will
   be capitalized

 - EDIT BEFORE RENAMING: This option will let you edit each filename 
   before it gets copied. When the edit requester appears, you
   can change the original name of a file, or leave it as it is by
   pressing return or clicking a 'Copy' gadget. If you click on a
   'Skip' gadget the current program will not get copied. And if you
   click on a 'Skip All' gadget all process will be canceled.

 - FILE DATE = CREATION DATE: File date of each copied file will be
   changed to a date of creation of each PS file

 - FILENOTE = CREATOR: Each file will get a file note (file comment)
   of a creator of each PS file



When you get all options selected to your needs you can click on a 'Go!'
gadget to start the copying process. A special window will  be opened,
telling you that files are being copied. If you want the process to be
canceled then simply press the 'Cancel' gagdet on that window. 

When you quit EPSRename all information about window position, selected
paths and options will be saved and will remain the same when you run
EPSRename the next time. Information is saved in the icon's tooltypes.
@endnode

